Greece, which has a province called Macedonia, claims that the name of the northern neighbor is a claim to its territory, and has vetoed Macedonia's accession to NATO and the EU.
In June, the two governments struck a deal based on the proposed new name, but nationalist opponents of the deal argue that the change would undermine the ethnic identity of the Slavic majority in Macedonia.
President Gheorghe Ivanov said that he would not vote in the referendum, and because of the boycott campaign, there are doubts whether the turnout will reach a minimum of 50%, which will allow the referendum to be considered valid.
The question in the referendum ballot is: “Do you support membership in NATO and the EU, provided that the agreement with Greece is accepted?”
Proponents of the name change, including Prime Minister Zoran Zaev, argue that this is the price that Macedonia, one of the countries formed after the breakup of Yugoslavia, should pay for joining such bodies as the EU and NATO.
“I came here today to vote for the future of the country, for the youth of Macedonia, so that it can live freely under the auspices of the European Union, because it means a safer life for all of us,” said Olivera Georgievska, 79, in Skopje.
Although the result of the vote does not entail legal obligations, enough members of parliament said they would support it to make it decisive.
A two-thirds vote in parliament is required to change the name.
The state election commission said that no reports of violations were received until 13:00.
However, turnout was only 16% compared to 34% in the last parliamentary elections in 2016, when 66% of registered voters threw their ballots into the ballot boxes.
“I came to vote for my children, our place in Europe,” said the 62-year-old Gyoze Tanevski in Skopje.
On September 30, 2018, in Strumica, Macedonia, Macedonian Prime Minister Zoran Zaev, his wife Zorica and his son Dushko voted in a referendum to change the country’s name, paving the way for accession to NATO and the European Union.
