“Our Sea”: Inland Bolivia hopes that the court will open its way to the Pacific Ocean
Sailors patrol an equipped fleet headquarters in La Paz.
Public buildings display an ocean-blue flag.
Marine bases from Lake Titicaca to the Amazon are painted with the motto: “The sea is ours by right.
We have to bring him back.”
In landlocked Bolivia, there is still a living memory of the loss of the coastline that ceded Chile in the bloody 19th-century conflict over natural resources, and there is a desire to swim again in the Pacific Ocean.
These hopes are now perhaps the strongest in decades, as Bolivia awaits an international court ruling on October 1 after five years of hearing the case.
“There is momentum in Bolivia, there is a spirit of unity and calm and, of course, it expects a positive result,” said Roberto Calsadia, a Bolivian diplomat.
Many Bolivians will watch the announcement of the ICJ decision on big screens across the country. They hope that the tribunal in The Hague will decide in favor of Bolivia, that after decades of fragmentary talks Chile will be forced to negotiate to grant Bolivia a sovereign exit to the sea.
Evo Morales, Bolivia’s charismatic indigenous president who faced opposition to his re-election next year, also has high hopes for a decision to be announced on Monday.
“We are very close to returning to the Pacific Ocean,” he promised at the end of August.
But some analysts believe that the court is unlikely to make a decision in favor of Bolivia, and if it does, little will change.
The UN body, based in the Netherlands, has no authority to award Chilean territory and said it would not determine the outcome of possible negotiations.
That the ICJ’s decision, taken just six months after the final arguments were put forward, indicates that the case “was not complicated,” said Pas Zarate, a Chilean expert on international law.
The case of Bolivia has not progressed, the last four years could contribute to a rollback.
“The issue of access to the sea was used by the current Bolivian administration,” Zarate said.
Morales’ militant rhetoric undermined the remnants of Chilean benevolence, she suggested.
Bolivia and Chile will continue the dialogue at some point, but after that it will be very difficult to hold discussions.
The two countries have not exchanged ambassadors since 1962.
Former President Eduardo Rodríguez Veltze, Bolivia’s representative in The Hague, disagreed that the court’s decision was unusually swift.
On Monday, Bolivia will have “an extraordinary opportunity to start a new era of relations with Chile and a chance to put an end to 139 years of disagreement with mutual benefit,” he said.
Calçadia also denied that Morales — still one of Latin America’s most popular presidents — used the maritime issue as a political crutch.
“Bolivia will never relinquish its right of access to the Pacific Ocean,” he added.
This resolution is an opportunity to see that we must leave the past behind.”
