John Edward: Knowledge of languages is mandatory for citizens of the world
Independent schools in Scotland maintain high standards of education, and in 2018 we again received excellent exam results, which are complemented by individual and collective success in sports, art, music and other fields.
These schools, with more than 30,000 students enrolled across Scotland, are represented by the Scottish Council of Independent Schools (SIC). They are committed to providing the best level of service for students and their parents.
Independent schools aim to prepare students for further and higher education, their chosen careers, and to make them citizens of the world.
As an educational sector that can design and implement an individual school curriculum, we see that modern languages continue to be a popular and desirable subject to choose from in schools.
Nelson Mandela said, “If you talk to a person in a language they understand, they perceive it with their mind.
If you talk to her in her native language, she feels it in her heart.”
This is a powerful reminder that we cannot use English alone if we want to build relationships and trust with people from other countries.
From the latest exam results this year, we see that in independent schools, languages lead in the rankings of the subjects with the best grades.
In total, 68% of students who studied foreign languages received a higher A score.
Data collected from 74 schools of the SRNSH showed that 72% of students received a higher A score from Chinese, while another 72% of those who studied German, 69% of those who studied French, and 63% of those who studied Spanish also got an A.
This suggests that independent schools in Scotland consider foreign languages as vital skills that children and young people will no doubt need in the future.
Now languages as a subject of choice are taught in the same way as NTIM subjects (science, engineering, engineering and mathematics), within the framework of independent school programs and in other institutions.
A survey conducted by the British Employment and Skills Commission in 2014 found that 17% of the reasons employers are unable to close vacancies are due to insufficient language skills.
Therefore, language skills are becoming increasingly necessary in preparing young people for their future careers.
As more and more promising positions require language skills, these skills are essential in a globalized world.
Regardless of the chosen career, if someone has learned a second language, he will have a real advantage in the future, because it is a lifelong skill.
The ability to communicate directly with people from other countries automatically gives a person who speaks several languages an advantage over competitors.
According to a YouGov survey of more than 4,000 UK adults in 2013, 75% could not speak a foreign language well enough to support a conversation, and French was the only language spoken by a double-digit percentage of people (15%).
That’s why investing in language teaching is important for today’s children.
Knowledge of several languages, especially the languages of developing countries, will provide children with a better chance of finding a full-fledged job.
In Scotland, each school will learn their own languages.
A number of schools will focus on more classical modern languages, while others will teach languages that are considered the most important for the UK from the perspective of 2020, such as Chinese or Japanese.
Regardless of your child’s interests in independent schools, it will always be possible to choose several languages to study with qualified teachers.
Scottish Independent Schools strive to create a learning environment that prepares children and equips them with the skills they need to succeed regardless of what the future holds for them.
Now it can not be denied that in the international business environment languages continue to be vital for the future of the country, so this should be reflected in education.
Modern languages should truly be considered “skills of international communication.”
Independent schools will continue to provide this choice, diversity and excellence to Scottish youth.
It's going to be fair.
John Edward is Director of the Scottish Council of Independent Schools.
