And while Ri repeated North Korea’s familiar complaints about Washington’s “step-by-step” approach to denuclearization, according to which North Korea would be rewarded for step-by-step steps, his statement proved important in that it did not reject the unilateral denuclearization that Pyongyang has done in the past.
Ree cited a joint statement by Kim Jong Un and Donald Trump at the first-ever summit between the incumbent U.S. president and North Korean leader in Singapore on June 12, when Kim called for work on “denuclearization of the Korean peninsula” and Trump promised security guarantees to North Korea.
North Korea is seeking a formal end to the 1950-53 Korean War, but the United States has said Pyongyang must first abandon nuclear weapons.
Washington has also resisted calls to ease tough international sanctions on North Korea.
"The United States insists on 'denuclearization first' and raises the level of pressure through sanctions to achieve its goal by force, and even opposes the 'declaration of the end of the war,'" Ri said.
