Harvard students take a course on how to relax enough
A new course at Harvard University this year has provided all of its students with more sleep. It is an attempt to combat the growing culture of steep learning all night after refueling with caffeine.
The teacher found that the world’s number one university students are often uneducated when it comes to the very basics of how to take care of themselves.
Charles Chaysler, a professor of sleep medicine at Harvard Medical School and a specialist at Brigham Women’s Hospital, has developed a course that he believes is the first such course in the United States.
He decided to start the course after giving a lecture on the effects of sleep deprivation on learning.
At the end, one girl came up to him and said, “Why am I being told this now, in my final year?”
“She said that no one ever told her about the importance of sleep, which surprised me,” the teacher told The Telegraph.
In the course, which was introduced for the first time this year, students are explained the basics of how good sleep habits help achieve academic and athletic results, as well as improve overall well-being.
Paul Barreira, professor of psychiatry at Harvard Medical School and executive director of the university’s medical services, said the university decided to introduce the course after it was discovered that students were severely deprived of sleep within a week.
The one-hour course includes a number of interactive tasks.
In one section, there is a picture of a dorm room where students click on cups of coffee, curtains, exercise machines and books to learn about the effects of caffeine and light, the impact of sleep deprivation on sports performance, and the importance of sleep-related routines.
Another section tells participants how prolonged sleep deprivation can increase the risk of heart attacks, stroke, depression, and cancer.
Further, the campus map with interactive icons encourages participants to think about their daily routine.
“We know that this will not change the behavior of students instantly.
But we believe they have a right to know, just as you have a right to know about the health effects of smoking cigarettes,” added Professor Chaysler.
A culture of pride in staying awake all night still exists, he added, noting that modern technology and the ever-increasing pressure on students mean the problem of sleep deprivation is growing.
Sufficient sleep of good quality should be the student’s “secret weapon” to combat stress, exhaustion and anxiety, even with an excess of weight, as sleep deprivation puts the brain in a mode of starvation that causes constant physical hunger, he said.
Raymond So, a 19-year-old Californian who studies chemical and physical biology, helped Professor Cheysler design the course after enrolling in one of his other courses last year during his first year at Harvard.
He said the course opened his eyes and inspired him to create a new course for the entire campus.
The next step, he hopes, will be to appeal to all graduate students with a request to undergo a similar program of study before coming to a competitive institution.
Professor Chaysler recommends that students put a reminder to go to bed, as well as to put on an alarm clock and be aware of the harmful effects of “blue light” that is emitted by electronic screens and LED lamps and can disrupt the circadian rhythm, which leads to problems with falling asleep.
