These cells are then able to “see” a protein that is common to many types of cancer. Then these cells are again injected into the patient.
The trial vaccine has shown promising results in patients with different types of cancer.
In one woman who received a vaccine that teaches the immune system to recognize malignant cells, ovarian cancer disappeared for more than 18 months.
The method involves extracting immune cells from the patient, changing them in the laboratory so that these cells can “see” the common cancer protein (HER2), and then re-injecting these cells into the patient.
Professor Jay Berzofsky of the U.S. National Cancer Institute, Bethesda, Maryland, said: “Our results show that we have received a very promising vaccine.”
“HER2 ‘stimulates the growth of several cancers’, including breast, ovarian, lung and colorectal cancers,” he explained.
A similar approach, which consists in extracting immune cells from patients and “teaching” them to target cancer cells, worked in the treatment of one type of leukemia.
