HIV/AIDS: China Says 14% Rise in New Cases
In China, a sharp increase of 14% in the number of citizens suffering from HIV and AIDS was reported.
According to health authorities, there are more than 820,000 patients in the country.
In the second quarter of 2018 alone, 40,000 new cases were reported.
In most cases, the disease was sexually transmitted, indicating a change in the past trend.
For a long time, HIV spread rapidly through infected blood during transfusions in some regions of China.
However, health officials said during a conference in Yunnan province, the number of people infected with HIV in this way has fallen to almost zero.
However, the number of people living with HIV and AIDS in China increased by 100,000 compared to the previous year.
Sexual transmission of HIV in time is a serious problem for the Chinese LGBT community.
The decriminalization of homosexuality in China took place in 1997, but the LGBT community often suffers from discrimination.
According to research, 70-90% of men who have sex with other men later marry women because of the dominance of conservative values in the country.
Transmission of the disease in most cases occurs as a result of improper use of protective means during sexual contact.
Since 2003, the Chinese government has pledged to ensure free access to HIV medicines, seeing this as a partial solution to the problem.
