Launched in 2012, the Global Citizen Festival is a continuation of the Global Poverty Project, an international non-governmental organization that hopes to eradicate poverty by increasing the number of people actively fighting it.
To get a free ticket to an event (unless you want to pay for a VIP ticket), visitors must complete a number of tasks or "actions", such as taking a volunteer project, writing an email to a world leader, making a phone call, or anything else to help draw attention to the organization's goal of eradicating poverty.
So are there any results already, because the organizers of Global Citizen have 12 years to achieve the goal?
Is the idea of rewarding for an act with a free concert really a brilliant way to convince people to demand action, or is it just another case of so-called “clictivism” when people feel they are really making a difference by signing an e-petition or posting on Twitter?
According to Global Citizen, since 2011, they have recorded 19 million “acts” of their supporters aimed at achieving various goals.
The organization claims that these actions prompted world leaders to announce more than $37 billion in funding and programs that will help change the lives of more than 2.25 billion people by 2030.
At the beginning of 2018, the group cited 390 financial commitments and public statements as an example of its performance, with at least $10 billion already collected and spent.
According to the group, the funds provided have already directly affected the lives of approximately 649 million people around the world.
