The introduction of a new German warship was postponed again
The state-of-the-art frigate of the German Navy was supposed to be put into operation in 2014 instead of outdated Cold War warships. However, according to local media, this will not happen at least until next year due to faulty systems and a rapid increase in costs.
According to the newspaper Die Zeit, received from the spokesman of the military department, the commissioning of the ship "Rheinland-Pfalz", the main ship of the series of the most modern frigates of the class "Baden-Württemberg", postponed until the first half of 2019.
The vessel was supposed to join the rest of the fleet in 2014, but problems that arose after the shipment harmed the implementation of the ambitious project.
The four ships of the Baden-Württemberg class, which the Navy ordered in 2007, are to replace the outdated frigates of the Bremen class.
It is clear that they will be equipped with a powerful gun, a set of anti-aircraft and anti-ship missiles, as well as some technologies to reduce visibility, in particular, radar, infrared and acoustic.
Another important feature is the longer maintenance period. It is expected that the new frigates will not be able to return to the port of deployment for about two years.
However, Die Zeit journalists warn that because of the constant delays, state-of-the-art warships, which were supposed to strengthen Germany’s military power at sea, will also become obsolete at the time of commissioning.
The long-suffering frigate F125 hit the headlines last year when the German navy officially refused to put the ship into operation and returned it to the Blohm + Voss shipyard in Hamburg.
This is the first time a warship has been returned to a shipbuilding company after delivery.
Little is known about the reasons for the return, but the German media mentioned significant "software and hardware defects" that rendered the warship unfit for military operations.
The shortcomings of the software are of particular importance, since the crew of the ship of the Baden-Württemberg class consists of about 120 sailors - this is only half the number of soldiers who served on the old frigates of the Bremen class.
In addition, it turned out that the ship has a significant excess weight, which worsens its performance and limits the possibilities for further modernization.
The Rhineland-Pfalz frigate is believed to be twice as heavy (7,000 tons) as the ships of the same class used by the Germans during World War II.
In addition to the faulty equipment, another problem was the total cost of the project, which also includes the cost of training the crew.
The expected 2.2 billion euros turned into a colossal 3.1 billion euros (3.6 billion US dollars).
Problems with obtaining new frigates have gained particular importance in the light of recent warnings about the decline of the German naval forces.
At the beginning of the year, Hans-Peter Bartels, the Bundestag’s commissioner for the armed forces, said that the navy of the country had “a small number of ships suitable for combat missions”.
The official said the situation had deteriorated rapidly over time, as the old ships were decommissioned and new ones did not arrive.
He expressed deep regret that none of the frigates of the Baden-Württemberg class were able to replenish the navy.
The National Trust will observe the secret lives of bats
The new study, which is being conducted on land tenure in the Scottish Highlands, aims to establish how bats use the landscape in search of food.
Scientists hope that the data will help shed light on the behavior of these unique flying mammals, in order to conduct measures for their preservation in the future.
In the gardens of Inverry in Wester-Rosse, scientists of the National Trust of Scotland will observe species such as the dwarf bat and the pygmy bat, as well as the common earfish and the water nightshade.
Special registrars will be placed in strategic locations on the territory of the land tenure to observe the behavior of bats during the season.
Employees and volunteers of the National Trust of Scotland will also conduct mobile research using handheld detectors.
Expert analysis of all recorded sounds will help to determine the frequency and affiliation of bat cries.
Then it is planned to develop a detailed map of the animal’s habitat and prepare a report to link the behavior of animals with their habitat.
Rob Dewar, a conservation adviser at the Scottish National Trust, hopes the findings will help determine which habitats are most important for bats and how they are used by each species.
This information will help to assess the effectiveness of habitat care measures (e.g. meadow formation) and identify optimal forest conservation practices for bats and other related species.
Over the past century, bat populations have declined significantly in Scotland and the UK.
They are threatened by active construction and development of territories, which deprives them of places of nesting.
Other negative factors include wind turbines and lighting, adhesive paper for flies, chemical treatment of building materials, as well as attacks of domestic cats.
The rats are not actually blind.
However, hunting at night makes the ears more effective at catching prey than the eyes.
They use a sophisticated echolocation technique to detect insects and obstacles on the flight path.
The National Trust of Scotland, which oversees over 270 historic buildings, 38 gardens of special importance, and 76,000 hectares of land nationwide, takes bat problems very seriously.
Ten specially trained experts regularly carry out surveys, inspections of nesting sites and sometimes even rescue operations.
The organization even created the first and only bat reserve in Scotland. It is located on the territory of the Trivee estate in the Dumfries and Galloway area. It sheltered eight of the ten bat species that live in Scotland.
The site manager David Thompson argues that this is the perfect place for them.
"There are excellent conditions for bats on the territory of the Trivet site," he assures.
"There are old buildings, many giant trees and other favorable living conditions.
But we still have a lot to learn about bats, and with the research we're doing here and elsewhere, we're going to be able to learn more about what they need to thrive."
He insists that it is very important to check the area for bats before carrying out any technical work, since the unintentional destruction of one nesting site for the breeding of young can kill up to 400 females with cubs, which is likely to destroy the entire local population.
Bats and their nests are protected by law. Animals are forbidden to kill, torture or disturb.
Elizabeth Ferrell, an officer at the Scottish Bat Conservation Centre, urged the public to join the organization's efforts.
She said, "We still have a lot to learn about our bats. We still haven't revealed the characteristics of many species' populations."
